Japan's biggest paper manufacturer, New Oji Paper  Co. Ltd., said Monday its pre-tax earnings declined 3.8 percent from a year  earlier to 10.5 billion yen (102 million dollars) in the year to March.
The company, a member of the Mitsui group with major pulp and paper  operations in Brazil, New Zealand and Canada, said sales grew 8.2 percent to  487 billion yen in the same period.
New Oji, formed through the merger of Oji Paper and Kanzakai Paper  Manufacturing in October 1993, forecast improved earnings of 11.5 billion yen  for the current year on sharply higher sales of 530 billion yen.
